--- In junit@y..., &quot;Vladimir Bossicard&quot; &lt;vbossica@t...&gt; wrote:
&gt; To solve the problem you have to understand that the framework 
creates an
&gt; object for each TestCase &#39;test&#39; method.  The idea is then to store 
information
&gt; about the file to execute while creating the TestCase instance (in 
the suite()
&gt; method).
&gt; 
&gt; One template can be:
&gt; 
&gt; import junit.framework.Test;
&gt; import junit.framework.TestCase;
&gt; import junit.framework.TestSuite;
&gt; 
&gt; public class BatchTest
&gt;         extends TestCase {
&gt; 
&gt;     String filename;
&gt; 
&gt;     public BatchTest( String name,
&gt;                       String filename ) {
&gt;         super( name );
&gt;         this.filename = filename;
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt;     public static Test suite() {
&gt;         TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
&gt;         for ( int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++ ) {
&gt;             suite.addTest( new BatchTest( &quot;testExecute&quot;, &quot;filename&quot; 
+ i ));
&gt;         }
&gt;         return suite;
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt;     public void testExecute() {
&gt;         System.out.println( &quot;executing: &quot; + filename );
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Now every test is executed independently from the other and you 
will have (in
&gt; this case) 10 different tests executed.
&gt; 
&gt; Note that you cannot use the reflection but need to call 
BatchTest.suite()
&gt; explicitely.
&gt; 
&gt; Is it what you wanted?
